[30;1m192 | [0m[35m            # Calculate an offset to extract the centermost embeddings of each window[0m
[30;1m193 | [0m[35m            stride = (self.max_pieces - self.num_start_tokens - self.num_end_tokens) // 2[0m
[30;1m194 | [0m[35m            stride_offset = stride // 2 + self.num_start_tokens[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m237[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m126 | [0m[35mWe don't need to specify anything for the "token delimiter",[0m

[30;1m106 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m16 | [0m[35mclass LinkingCoverageTransitionFunction(CoverageTransitionFunction):[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m    Combines both linking and coverage on top of the ``BasicTransitionFunction`` (which is just an[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m    LSTM decoder with attention).  This adds the ability to consider `linked` actions in addition[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m    to global (embedded) actions, and it adds a coverage penalty over the `output action sequence`,[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m    combining the :class:`LinkingTransitionFunction` with the :class:`CoverageTransitionFunction`.[0m

[30;1m28 | [0m[35m## You specify laziness in the `DatasetReader` constructor[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35mIf you look at the [constructor](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/blob/master/allennlp/data/datas[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35mfor the base `DatasetReader` class, you can see that it takes a single parameter:[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35m```python[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m608[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/allennlp_pvt_nightly-0.9.1.dev201910011800/tutorials/getting_started/laziness.md[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(advpack\.dll|appvlp|at|atbroker|bash|bginfo|bitsadmin|cdb|certutil|cl_invocation\.ps1|cl_mutexverifiers\.ps1|cmd|cmdkey|cmstp|comsvcs\.dll|control|csc|cscript|csi|devtoolslauncher|dfsvc|diskshadow|dnscmd|dnx|dotnet|dxcap|esentutl|eventvwr|excel|expand|extexport|extrac32|findstr|forfiles|ftp|gfxdownloadwrapper|gpscript|hh|ie4uinit|ieadvpack\.dll|ieaframe\.dll|ic|infdefaultinstall|installutil|jsc|makecab|manage-bde\.wsf|mavinject|mftrace|microsoft\.workflow\.compiler|mmc|msbuild|msconfig|msdeploy|msdt|mshta|mshtml\.dll|msc|msxsl|netsh|odbcconf|pcalua|pcwrun|pcwutl\.dll|pester\.bat|powerpnt|presentationhost|pubprn\.vbs|rcsi|reg|regasm|regedit|register-cimprovider|regsvcs|regsvr32|rpcping|rundll32|runonce|runscripthelper|sc|schtasks|scriptrunner|setupapi\.dll|shdocvw\.dll|shell32\.dll|slmgr\.vbs|sqldumper|sqlps|sqltoolsps|squirrel|syncappvpublishingserver|syncappvpublishingserver\.vbs|syssetup\.dll|te|tracker|tttracer|update|url\.dll|verclsid|vsjitdebugger|wab|winrm\.vbs|winword|wmic|wscript|wsl|wsreset|xwizard|zipfldr\.dll)\s[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mIn these cases[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35myou'll want your `DatasetReader` to be "lazy"; that is,[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mto create and yield up instances as needed rather than all at once.[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mThis tutorial will show both you how to create `DatasetReader`s[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mthat allow this lazy behavior, and how to handle this laziness[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m609[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/allennlp_pvt_nightly-0.9.1.dev201910011800/tutorials/getting_started/laziness.md[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m201 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m202 | [0m[35mIf you have a sense for how many instances can fit in memory, you can specify[0m
[30;1m203 | [0m[35mthe `max_instances_in_memory` parameter. For instance, if you were to set that[0m
[30;1m204 | [0m[35mto 3200, the iterator would load 3200 instances at a time into memory,[0m
[30;1m205 | [0m[35mpotentially shuffle them, and then create 100 batches of size 32 and yield[0m
[30;1m206 | [0m[35mthem up before loading the next 3200 instances.[0m
[30;1m207 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m610[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m94 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35mWhat this means is that the result is an iterable that calls the provided[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35mfunction each time it's iterated over. With the lambda we passed it,[0m
[30;1m97 | [0m[35mit will call `self._read(file_path)` each time it's iterated over.[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35mIn other words, if you implement your own dataset reader and do something like the following:[0m
[30;1m100 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m611[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m96 | [0m[35mfunction each time it's iterated over. With the lambda we passed it,[0m

[30;1m9 | [0m[35mclass PytorchSeq2SeqWrapper(Seq2SeqEncoder):[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35m    Pytorch's RNNs have two outputs: the hidden state for every time step, and the hidden state at[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35m    the last time step for every layer.  We just want the first one as a single output.  This[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m    wrapper pulls out that output, and adds a :func:`get_output_dim` method, which is useful if you[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m    want to, e.g., define a linear + softmax layer on top of this to get some distribution over a[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m620[0m[34m of [0m[33m2034[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

[30;1m11 | [0m[35m    Pytorch's RNNs have two outputs: the hidden state for every time step, and the hidden state at[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35m    the last time step for every layer.  We just want the first one as a single output.  This[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m    wrapper pulls out that output, and adds a :func:`get_output_dim` method, which is useful if you[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m    want to, e.g., define a linear + softmax layer on top of this to get some distribution over a[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m    set of labels.  The linear layer needs to know its input dimension before it is called, and you[0m

[30;1m33 | [0m[35m    end_tokens : ``List[str]``, optional[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m        If given, these tokens will be added to the end of every string we tokenize.[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m    """[0m

[30;1m16 | [0m[35m    There are two different kinds of batching we need to distinguish here.  First, there's the[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m    batch of training instances passed to ``model.forward()``.  We'll use "batch" and[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m    ``batch_size`` to refer to this through the docs and code.  We additionally batch together[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m    computation for several states at the same time, where each state could be from the same[0m

[30;1m537 | [0m[35mThe one that's non-obvious is `--include-package`.[0m
[30;1m538 | [0m[35mThe decorator that registers your classes only runs[0m
[30;1m539 | [0m[35mwhen the module containing it is loaded. And the `allennlp` execution[0m
[30;1m540 | [0m[35mscript has no way of knowing it needs to load the modules containing[0m
[30;1m541 | [0m[35myour custom code (indeed, it doesn't even know those modules exist).[0m
[30;1m542 | [0m[35mAnd so the `--include-package` argument tells AllenNLP to load the[0m
[30;1m543 | [0m[35mspecified modules (and in particular run their `register` decorators)[0m

[30;1m403 | [0m[35m## Making Predictions[0m
[30;1m404 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m405 | [0m[35mAs in the original PyTorch tutorial, we'd like to look at the predictions our model generates.[0m
[30;1m406 | [0m[35mAllenNLP contains a `Predictor` abstraction that takes inputs, converts them to `Instance`s,[0m
[30;1m407 | [0m[35mfeeds them through your model, and returns JSON-serializable results.[0m
[30;1m408 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m298 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m299 | [0m[35mThe key functionality of both of these systems is to (1) go from a logical form or program to a[0m
[30;1m300 | [0m[35msequence of actions that the parser can output, (2) define the allowed actions at each timestep[0m
[30;1m301 | [0m[35m(which is determined by the current grammar state), and (3) go from a sequence of actions back to a[0m

[30;1m303 | [0m[35mof our two options (for example, by using a compiler's abstract syntax tree), then you can bypass[0m

[30;1m219 | [0m[35mthe LSTM decoder, we also include those inputs (and their mask) as part of the `RnnStatelet`.[0m

[30;1m256 | [0m[35m#### index. We use the <code>Vocabulary</code> to find how many embeddings we need and[0m
[30;1m257 | [0m[35m#### our <code>EMBEDDING_DIM</code> parameter to specify the output dimension.[0m
[30;1m258 | [0m[35m#### It's also possible to start with pre-trained embeddings (for example, GloVe vectors),[0m
[30;1m259 | [0m[35m#### but there's no need to do that on this tiny toy dataset.[0m
